{
  "doc_id": "50853",
  "text": "Immune molecules are increasingly implicated for their role in synaptic plasticity mechanisms within the brain, including memory. The proinflammatory cytokine interleukin-1␤ (IL-1␤) is induced within the hippocampus (HP) in response to normal learning and is critical for maintaining long-term potentiation (LTP) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Moreover, mice lacking IL-1␤ or its type 1 receptor exhibit markedly impaired HP-dependent learning and memory [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In contrast, high levels of IL-1␤ can profoundly impair memory [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] and are associated with Alzheimer's disease (AD) and other neurodegenerative disorders [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . These data suggest that physiological levels of IL-1␤ are necessary for normal memory, whereas concentrations that are either too low or too high impair memory [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] .",
